04127nam a22006255i 9780271048994DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212007pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710489947 a10.1515/97802710489942doi  a(DE-B1597)583878  a(OCoLC)1262307540  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0040002bisacsh04a305.5/6209732221 aArnold, Kathleen R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerica's New Working Class :bRace, Gender, and Ethnicity in a Biopolitical Age /cKathleen R. Arnold. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Globalization, Prerogative Power, and the New Working Class -- t1 Asceticism, Biopower, and the Poor -- t2 Domestic War: Locke's Concept of Prerogative -- t3 Exploitation and the New Working Class -- t4 Antagonism and Exploitation: The Importance of Biopower -- t5 War and "Love" -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday's political controversy over immigration highlights the plight of the working class in this country as perhaps no other issue has recently done. The political status of immigrants exposes the power dynamics of the "new working class," which includes the former labor aristocracy, women, and people of color. This new working class suffers exploitation in advanced industrial countries as the social cost of capitalism's success in a neoliberal and globalized political economy. Paradoxically, as borders become more open, they are also increasingly fortified, subjecting many workers to the suspension of law.In this book, Kathleen Arnold analyzes the role of the state's "prerogative power" in creating and sustaining this condition of severe inequality for the most marginalized sectors of our population in the United States. Drawing on a wide range of theoretical literature from Locke to Marx and Agamben (whose notion of "bare life" features prominently in her construal of this as a "biopolitical" era), she focuses attention especially on the values of asceticism derived from the Protestant work ethic to explain how they function as ideological justification for the exercise of prerogative power by the state.As a counter to this repressive set of values, she develops the notion of "authentic love" borrowed from Simone de Beauvoir as a possible approach for dealing with the complex issues of exploitation in liberal democracy today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civil Rights.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271048994zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271048994423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271048994.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK